WEBVTT

00:00.100 --> 00:03.135
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Now... on "Ice Road Truckers":</i>

00:07.440 --> 00:11.276
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>The drivers go where</i>
<i>they've never gone before.</i>

00:11.278 --> 00:14.346
<i>Todd:</i>
<i>This is Hudson Bay right here.</i>
<i>The ocean.</i>

00:14.348 --> 00:16.648
We are building our own road.

00:16.650 --> 00:19.852
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>No big rigs,</i>

00:19.854 --> 00:21.186
<i>no roads...</i>

00:21.188 --> 00:24.256
<i>Todd:</i>
<i>Whoo-hoo!</i>

00:24.258 --> 00:26.959
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>As the rivals risk at all.</i>

00:26.961 --> 00:29.061
Todd:
This is the adventure
of a lifetime right here.

00:29.063 --> 00:30.129
I tell you what.

00:30.131 --> 00:31.997
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>At the end of the earth.</i>

00:35.068 --> 00:45.177
♪

00:45.179 --> 00:50.549
♪

00:50.551 --> 01:00.893
♪

01:07.967 --> 01:09.735
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Throughout the north,</i>

01:09.737 --> 01:15.274
<i>signs of an early spring</i>
<i>are everywhere.</i>

01:15.276 --> 01:16.942
Lisa:
Whoo-hoo.

01:19.479 --> 01:22.314
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>The winter roads</i>
<i>are melting away.</i>

01:24.951 --> 01:27.619
Whew, what am I doing out here?

01:30.190 --> 01:32.191
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>And the truckers'</i>
<i>window of opportunity</i>

01:32.193 --> 01:35.194
<i>is rapidly closing.</i>

01:35.196 --> 01:37.396
<i>Alex:</i>
<i>Well, it's closed.</i>

01:37.398 --> 01:39.631
<i>They blocked it with a grater.</i>

01:39.633 --> 01:42.935
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>To stay in business,</i>

01:42.937 --> 01:45.237
<i>companies are hunting</i>
<i>for remaining trails</i>

01:45.239 --> 01:47.239
<i>that are still open.</i>

01:47.241 --> 01:48.607
<i>And in Winnipeg...</i>

01:48.609 --> 01:49.942
<i>Todd:</i>
<i>What's up buddy?</i>

01:49.944 --> 01:52.044
Mark:
I've got a little crazy idea
I want to run by you.

01:52.046 --> 01:54.880
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>The boss may have found one,</i>

01:54.882 --> 01:58.784
<i>but it could be the biggest</i>
<i>gamble in Polar's history.</i>

01:58.786 --> 02:01.520
<i>Mark:</i>
<i>I got a call from a customer</i>
<i>he's up and Seal River.</i>

02:01.522 --> 02:04.123
It's a wilderness camp up
there, Seal River Lodge.

02:04.125 --> 02:06.258
<i>He needs an excavator</i>
<i>brought in.</i>

02:06.260 --> 02:11.163
<i>Mark:</i>
<i>They want to see if we can pull</i>
<i>sleighs across Hudson Bay</i>

02:11.165 --> 02:13.565
into Seal River.

02:14.934 --> 02:16.368
<i>Todd:</i>
<i>Hudson Bay, like, the ocean?</i>

02:16.370 --> 02:18.303
Mark: Yeah, it's--
Todd: Like the ocean, ocean.

02:18.305 --> 02:22.641
I, I mean--
Mark: This is beyond
ice road trucking.

02:23.643 --> 02:27.045
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Seal River is a tributary</i>
<i>in the Hudson Bay.</i>

02:27.047 --> 02:28.514
<i>And the only way to reach it</i>

02:28.516 --> 02:31.683
<i>is by flying 600 miles</i>
<i>north of Winnipeg</i>

02:31.685 --> 02:34.052
<i>to the town of Churchill.</i>

02:34.054 --> 02:38.924
<i>And then driving across</i>
<i>the frozen ocean.</i>

02:38.926 --> 02:44.329
<i>But on this remote ice,</i>
<i>big rigs aren't permitted.</i>

02:44.331 --> 02:48.167
<i>The only way to haul freight</i>
<i>is with a cat train.</i>

02:48.169 --> 02:49.735
<i>Mark:</i>
<i>The Hudson Bay,</i>

02:49.737 --> 02:54.039
I mean that's a massive,
massive body of water.

02:54.041 --> 02:57.309
<i>We've delivered with trucks</i>
<i>for years,</i>

02:57.311 --> 02:58.810
<i>and now we want to show that</i>

02:58.812 --> 03:01.013
we can move freight
with other means.

03:01.015 --> 03:02.848
With cat trains and sleighs.

03:02.850 --> 03:05.450
<i>And we want to prove</i>
<i>to the world that we can</i>
<i>get this done.</i>

03:05.452 --> 03:07.152
<i>Todd:</i>
<i>There's no road,</i>
<i>there is no nothing.</i>

03:07.154 --> 03:09.388
It's just basically,
you just take off in the--

03:09.390 --> 03:11.190
open tundra and get going.
Mark: I'm basically--

03:11.192 --> 03:13.358
I'm basically giving you
GPS coordinates

03:13.360 --> 03:15.394
and you're going to have to
figure out a way to get there.

03:15.396 --> 03:17.095
Oh, (bleep)!

03:17.097 --> 03:19.665
<i>Mark:</i>
<i>You might get into some</i>
<i>open water,</i>

03:19.667 --> 03:23.669
you might get in to some, you
know, 10, 12 foot ice ridges.

03:23.671 --> 03:26.238
<i>I mean, you're going to be</i>
<i>going through stuff you've</i>
<i>never seen before.</i>

03:26.240 --> 03:27.806
Wow.

03:27.808 --> 03:29.875
<i>Mark:</i>
<i>This is going to make history</i>
<i>for us.</i>

03:29.877 --> 03:31.343
<i>You in?</i>

03:33.813 --> 03:35.247
Heck, yeah. I'm in.
Mark: Okay.

03:35.249 --> 03:36.348
Todd: I am ready to do it.
Mark: Okay, should I pull
the trigger?

03:36.350 --> 03:37.516
Should I say we're in?

03:37.518 --> 03:40.953
Yeah, do it.
Tell them we'll do it.

03:40.955 --> 03:42.854
(Dialling)

03:43.923 --> 03:45.591
Mark:
Hey, how are you doing?

03:45.593 --> 03:47.492
Yeah, we can, we can commit
to that no problem.

03:47.494 --> 03:50.796
I got the best guy
sitting here.

03:50.798 --> 03:53.732
Two, (sighs) two drivers? No.

03:55.835 --> 03:57.569
<i>No, I understand.</i>

03:57.571 --> 04:00.439
No, I'll, I'll, I'll find,
I'll find a second one.

04:00.441 --> 04:03.141
Yeah, no. I, I, I-
I know it's last minute and--

04:03.143 --> 04:06.578
but you can count on me.
Bye-bye.

04:06.580 --> 04:09.348
Two loads now, bud.
(Sighs heavily)

04:09.350 --> 04:12.017
Now, what are we going to do?

04:12.019 --> 04:13.719
<i>Mark:</i>
<i>I called to check</i>
<i>on the Churchill load</i>

04:13.721 --> 04:15.621
<i>and then I'm being told</i>
<i>it's two runs.</i>

04:15.623 --> 04:19.324
All my best drivers are
scattered all over Manitoba
and Ontario.

04:19.326 --> 04:21.026
I don't know what to do.

04:21.028 --> 04:24.196
<i>Who can we find? Somebody that</i>
<i>knows what they're doing,</i>

04:24.198 --> 04:26.999
and somebody that
is gonna watch your back?

04:27.001 --> 04:29.901
<i>Todd:</i>
<i>We just need somebody</i>
<i>we can trust.</i>

04:29.903 --> 04:33.238
I have an idea, but I don't know
if I want to say it or not.

04:42.348 --> 04:44.783
(Tools clattering)

04:44.785 --> 04:46.652
Lisa:
Last one.

04:46.654 --> 04:49.321
<i>Mark:</i>
<i>Hey, knock-knock?</i>

04:49.323 --> 04:52.457
<i>Lisa:</i>
<i>Are you lost?</i>

04:52.459 --> 04:54.826
<i>Mark:</i>
<i>I wanted to pop in and uh,</i>
<i>present,</i>

04:54.828 --> 04:57.796
<i>possibly a business</i>
<i>opportunity to you both.</i>

04:57.798 --> 04:59.731
I got something that's crazy

04:59.733 --> 05:03.902
and crazy, I figure,
is right up both your alleys.

05:05.004 --> 05:07.406
Churchill.

05:07.408 --> 05:09.741
Not driving a truck, but pulling
odd wells and cat trains.

05:09.743 --> 05:12.377
It's across Hudson Bay
which is pretty wild.

05:12.379 --> 05:14.713
<i>It was supposed to be one run,</i>
<i>it turned into two.</i>

05:14.715 --> 05:17.549
<i>We need to have somebody</i>
<i>that can run with Todd.</i>

05:17.551 --> 05:20.552
Todd:
I gotta have someone who knows
what the hell they're doing.

05:20.554 --> 05:22.921
I'm not gonna go with somebody
I have to babysit.

05:22.923 --> 05:25.023
Uh, we both said,
"Uh, you know what,

05:25.025 --> 05:28.894
Lisa should go with him
on this run."

05:28.896 --> 05:32.331
<i>Can you help us out?</i>

05:32.333 --> 05:34.800
I want to go to Churchill.

05:34.802 --> 05:36.168
Darrell: Oh yeah?
Lisa: Yes.

05:36.170 --> 05:38.003
It's gonna be a lifetime
experience.

05:38.005 --> 05:42.341
I mean, without a shadow
of a doubt so.

05:43.910 --> 05:45.877
<i>What do you say, Lisa?</i>
<i>You want to do this run</i>
<i>with me, or what?</i>

05:45.879 --> 05:50.148
<i>Mark:</i>
<i>You think we can team up</i>
<i>and get this done without--</i>

05:50.150 --> 05:51.983
Darrell: Without bumping heads?
Mark, Todd: Yeah.

05:51.985 --> 05:54.186
Well, I'd rather work with ya,
then fight with ya.

05:54.188 --> 05:55.620
<i>So, let's make it work.</i>

05:55.622 --> 05:56.888
Lisa: Great.
Todd: Let's do it!

05:56.890 --> 05:59.424
Mark:
Let's go, guys.

05:59.426 --> 06:01.960
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>The rival companies</i>
<i>are aligning forces</i>

06:01.962 --> 06:05.364
<i>to tackle one of the most</i>
<i>remote and unforgiving</i>

06:05.366 --> 06:07.466
<i>destinations on the planet.</i>

06:07.468 --> 06:11.036
<i>Further north than either</i>
<i>has dared to travel.</i>

06:11.038 --> 06:14.039
<i>And the mission to man</i>
<i>the 50 tonne cat train</i>

06:14.041 --> 06:18.009
<i>is unlike anything</i>
<i>they've attempted before.</i>

06:18.011 --> 06:20.045
<i>Darrell:</i>
<i>This run to Churchill</i>
<i>is an opportunity</i>

06:20.047 --> 06:22.948
for both of these companies
to make history together.

06:22.950 --> 06:25.917
I mean, they're going to the
end of the earth and beyond.

06:25.919 --> 06:29.020
<i>This is huge in the world</i>
<i>of trucking.</i>

06:29.022 --> 06:31.056
<i>Mark:</i>
<i>With both of these companies</i>
<i>coming together,</i>

06:31.058 --> 06:34.659
<i>it's gonna be really</i>
<i>challenging, but, you know,</i>

06:34.661 --> 06:38.663
bragging rights for both of us
if we can accomplish this.

06:38.665 --> 06:41.199
<i>Lisa:</i>
<i>I am so excited that I get</i>
<i>to go to Churchill</i>

06:41.201 --> 06:45.036
because now that is another
check mark off my bucket list.

06:56.682 --> 06:58.784
<i>Todd:</i>
<i>My goodness!</i>

06:58.786 --> 07:00.886
<i>It's amazing.</i>

07:00.888 --> 07:03.422
If you look across there,
it's just--

07:03.424 --> 07:05.624
Basically, it's gonna-
It's an obstacle course.

07:05.626 --> 07:07.893
Look at those pressure ridges
from the ice to water,

07:07.895 --> 07:11.329
from the pressure, it bulges
that ice up in certain areas.

07:11.331 --> 07:13.899
And you literally have to
freaking weave in and out

07:13.901 --> 07:15.300
and get around them-
Oh my God...

07:15.302 --> 07:17.736
I, I don't know how
this is all gonna work.

07:17.738 --> 07:20.639
It's not easy.

07:20.641 --> 07:29.247
♪

07:29.249 --> 07:31.583
(Engine idling)

07:33.352 --> 07:36.254
Todd:
You want these first? Third?

07:37.423 --> 07:39.791
Make sure we get all the load
on there that we need to take.

07:39.793 --> 07:41.259
We don't want to leave
anything behind.

07:41.261 --> 07:43.628
'Cause it's one major trip in.

07:43.630 --> 07:45.263
<i>It's vitally important</i>
<i>to get everything we need</i>

07:45.265 --> 07:48.667
<i>on these track machines</i>
<i>to get it all delivered.</i>

07:48.669 --> 07:51.536
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>The excavator and building</i>
<i>supplies are loaded up</i>

07:51.538 --> 07:52.838
for the journey.

07:52.840 --> 07:53.672
(Clank)

07:53.674 --> 07:54.673
(Grunts)

07:54.675 --> 07:56.541
Todd:
Ready to go.

07:56.543 --> 07:59.744
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>And as an added precaution</i>
<i>an emergency driver</i>

07:59.746 --> 08:04.249
<i>will ride in the excavator</i>
<i>in case disaster strikes.</i>

08:06.519 --> 08:09.588
Lisa:
About ready to leave.

08:09.590 --> 08:12.357
No seat belts.

08:12.359 --> 08:13.725
(Engine humming)

08:13.727 --> 08:15.727
Todd:
Looks pretty basic.

08:15.729 --> 08:18.530
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Now, the team must</i>
<i>familiarize themselves</i>

08:18.532 --> 08:22.734
with a decades old
track machine.

08:22.736 --> 08:26.204
Todd:
She's a beast, boy!
I'll tell you what.

08:26.206 --> 08:29.207
<i>Never seen anything like her.</i>

08:31.244 --> 08:34.513
That's it, that's fifth gear
right there.

08:34.515 --> 08:39.918
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Todd takes off</i>
<i>with the giant excavator.</i>

08:43.556 --> 08:44.789
(Laughs)

08:47.627 --> 08:50.996
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>And Lisa gets moving with her</i>
<i>load of building supplies.</i>

08:57.336 --> 08:59.905
(Engine puttering)

09:01.173 --> 09:06.077
♪

09:06.079 --> 09:10.115
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Even though the track rigs are</i>
<i>slower and heavier than trucks,</i>

09:10.117 --> 09:12.684
<i>only a vehicle with treads</i>
<i>can maneuver</i>

09:12.686 --> 09:15.287
<i>over the uneven landscape.</i>

09:15.289 --> 09:17.122
<i>Lisa:</i>
<i>Oh, this is truly awesome</i>
<i>for Polar</i>

09:17.124 --> 09:19.024
and Darrell at my company
coming together

09:19.026 --> 09:20.559
and hauling these loads
out here.

09:20.561 --> 09:24.195
It's teamwork,
instead of fighting for once.

09:35.875 --> 09:37.909
<i>And it's gonna take me</i>
<i>some getting used to</i>

09:37.911 --> 09:41.546
<i>because it's tracks instead</i>
<i>of tires.</i>

09:41.548 --> 09:46.351
I'm just gonna goes slow.
(Laughs)

09:46.353 --> 09:49.120
(Engine humming)

09:49.122 --> 09:52.791
<i>Todd:</i>
<i>This is unbelievable!</i>
<i>Whoo hoo!</i>

09:54.393 --> 09:56.428
This is an adventure
of a lifetime, right here,

09:56.430 --> 09:58.163
I tell you what.

09:58.165 --> 10:00.165
Look at that (bleep) out there!

10:00.167 --> 10:03.902
<i>Look at these heaves of ice,</i>
<i>man. Wow!</i>

10:06.572 --> 10:10.609
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Todd and Lisa will have to</i>
<i>survive miles of untouched ice,</i>

10:10.611 --> 10:12.577
<i>dozens of pressure ridges</i>

10:12.579 --> 10:16.548
and limitless peaks and valleys
<i>before they reach Seal River.</i>

10:16.550 --> 10:18.817
(Engine humming)

10:18.819 --> 10:24.456
<i>Todd:</i>
<i>I cannot believe I'm in a 1975</i>
<i>Bombardier old track machine</i>

10:24.458 --> 10:27.726
pulling a sled with an
excavator. (Laughs)

10:27.728 --> 10:30.595
Who would have ever thought,
huh?

10:30.597 --> 10:33.665
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>But the convoy is ready</i>
<i>to meet the challenge head on</i>

10:33.667 --> 10:35.934
<i>and to deliver for their</i>
<i>companies.</i>

10:47.313 --> 10:49.481
(Engine humming)

10:49.483 --> 10:51.516
<i>Todd:</i>
<i>This ain't even an ice road.</i>

10:51.518 --> 10:53.985
We are building our own road.

10:55.888 --> 10:59.090
<i>I feel like I'm on top</i>
<i>of the world!</i>

11:09.635 --> 11:13.138
<i>On the rapidly thawing winter</i>
<i>roads...</i>   <i>rrator:</i>

11:13.140 --> 11:15.407
<i>Mike:</i>
<i>Daddy likes it rough.</i>

11:15.409 --> 11:17.575
(Truck jostling)
(Grunts)

11:17.577 --> 11:19.644
(Laughs)
Oh yeah.

11:19.646 --> 11:21.513
<i>This weather is crazy.</i>

11:21.515 --> 11:26.384
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Mother Nature has thrown Polar</i>
<i>driver Mike Simmons a curve.</i>

11:26.386 --> 11:32.023
<i>Dumping 3 feet of wet snow on</i>
<i>the trail to you Utik Lake.</i>

11:32.025 --> 11:34.259
She's gonna be a real
rough ride.

11:34.261 --> 11:40.298
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Add it's obscuring potholes</i>
<i>and torn up muskeg from days</i>
<i>of melting,</i>

11:40.300 --> 11:42.434
<i>Making a rough ride</i>
<i>for the newcomer</i>

11:42.436 --> 11:45.403
<i>and his 10 tonne crates</i>
<i>of pontoon boats.</i>

11:45.405 --> 11:49.207
<i>Mike:</i>
<i>I got a couple seacans</i>
<i>on a tandem highboy here.</i>

11:49.209 --> 11:53.611
Breakups coming a little faster
<i>than anybody has anticipated.</i>

11:53.613 --> 11:54.646
(Loud crash)

11:54.648 --> 11:56.915
Ow! Oh boy!

11:56.917 --> 11:58.883
<i>No more bumps!</i>

11:58.885 --> 12:02.320
<i>Art:</i>
<i>How you doin' back there,</i>
<i>You all right b'y?</i>

12:02.322 --> 12:04.189
Hey Art, what's up?

12:04.191 --> 12:06.157
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>But Mike's not alone</i>
<i>on the mission.</i>

12:09.562 --> 12:11.129
Yeah, like, all the time, eh?

12:11.131 --> 12:13.098
<i>Mike:</i>
<i>(Laughs) Lovely.</i>

12:13.100 --> 12:16.267
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Up ahead, Art Burke leads</i>
<i>the two man convoy</i>

12:16.269 --> 12:18.970
<i>with a 12 tonne load</i>
<i>of building supplies.</i>

12:18.972 --> 12:22.540
<i>The other half of the season's</i>
<i>last haul into Utik.</i>

12:22.542 --> 12:23.808
Art:
Mike is right behind me.

12:23.810 --> 12:25.043
This time, I'm not waiting
for him.

12:25.045 --> 12:26.177
So he better pick up his socks.

12:26.179 --> 12:27.879
It's the last time
we run together.

12:27.881 --> 12:31.249
First you get good,
then you get fast.

12:31.251 --> 12:32.650
(Laughs)

12:34.887 --> 12:37.455
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>On their last trip together...</i>

12:37.457 --> 12:39.324
Art:
Let the games begin.

12:39.326 --> 12:41.259
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Art put Mike through</i>
<i>the wringer</i>

12:41.261 --> 12:44.863
<i>by setting a blistering pace.</i>

12:44.865 --> 12:48.133
Mike:
Art has got his foot into it.

12:48.135 --> 12:50.368
<i>Art:</i>
<i>Boy, oh boy,</i>
<i>you gonna have to catch up.</i>

12:50.370 --> 12:52.670
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>And the rookie struggled</i>
<i>to keep up.</i>

12:52.672 --> 12:54.205
(Loud crash)
(Grunts)

12:54.207 --> 12:55.907
(Bleep) me!

12:55.909 --> 12:57.308
(Laughs)

13:01.046 --> 13:02.947
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>Now...</i>

13:02.949 --> 13:05.250
Art:
All right, buddy, hammer down.

13:05.252 --> 13:10.355
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>The veteran's putting Mike</i>
<i>to the test once again.</i>

13:10.357 --> 13:11.990
Mike:
I'm a little more seasoned now

13:11.992 --> 13:13.758
and I'm confident
that keeping up with Art

13:13.760 --> 13:15.393
is not to be a problem,

13:15.395 --> 13:18.429
despite his ridiculous pace
that he sets.

13:18.431 --> 13:20.999
<i>Narrator:</i>
<i>And, with a little experience</i>
<i>under his belt</i>

